  <h2 id="q1">Q1: Mutable Default Arguments</h2>
  <pre><code class="language-python">def append_to(element, target=[]):
    target.append(element)
    return target

print(append_to(1))  # [1]
print(append_to(2))  # [1, 2] NOT [2]!</code></pre>
  <p><strong>Why:</strong> Default arguments are evaluated once at function definition. The list object is shared across calls.</p>

  <h2 id="q2">Q2: Generator Memory Efficiency</h2>
  <pre><code class="language-python">def fibonacci():
    a, b = 0, 1
    while True:
        yield a
        a, b = b, a + b

# Lazy evaluation O(1) memory regardless of how many values consumed
fib = fibonacci()
first_10 = [next(fib) for _ in range(10)]</code></pre>
